div.div:
Multiple Correspondance Analysis (MCA) is used to identify corresponding features between multiple studies or experiments. Those can be lists of differentially expressed genes or pathways, or detected variants/haplotypes in common between experiment.
The goal here is to quickly distil multiple experiments to identify corresponding results given different environments (experimental treatment/condition) and a arbitrary number of observations (variants or genes expressed)
